  Given a topological space <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>, let <fr:tex>\mathcal {O}( X )</fr:tex> denote its class of opens.
</fr:p><fr:p>
  As <fr:tex>\mathcal {O}( X )</fr:tex> is a frame, we can view this as a mapping <fr:tex>\mathcal {O}  :  \mathbf {Top}   \to     \mathbf {Frm}</fr:tex>, which we can then extend to a <fr:em>contravariant functor</fr:em>:
  <fr:ol><fr:li>let <fr:tex>f : X  \to  Y</fr:tex> be a continuous map of topological spaces,</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:tex>\mathcal {O} (f)</fr:tex> should then be mapping from the frame <fr:tex>\mathcal {O}( Y )</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>\mathcal {O}( X )</fr:tex>,</fr:li>
    <fr:li>
      given some <fr:tex>U  \in   \mathcal {O}( Y )</fr:tex>, <fr:tex>\mathcal {O} (f)(U) := f^{-1}(U)</fr:tex> which is in
      <fr:tex>\mathcal {O}( X )</fr:tex> precisely by the continuity of <fr:tex>f</fr:tex>.
    </fr:li></fr:ol></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:contributions></fr:contributions><fr:context></fr:context><fr:related></fr:related><fr:backlinks><fr:tree
